<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bank of America and federal prosecutors have accelerated their negotiations to resolve an investigation into the bankâs sale of troubled mortgage securities before the financial crisis, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/30/bank-of-america-ordered-to-pay-nearly-1-3-billion-in-mortgage-case">Michael Corkery and Ben Protess write in DealBook</a></b>. But the two sides remain far apart on crucial issues, and a settlement remained elusive late on Wednesday, even after the bank raised its offer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bankâs lawyers and Justice Department prosecutors are said to have met in Washington on Wednesday to <b>discuss the size of a potential cash penalty</b>. Heading into the meeting, the Justice Department was demanding roughly $17 billion to settle the case, more than $10 billion in the form of a cash penalty and the rest in so-called soft dollar payments to help struggling homeowners. The bank was offering a total of $13 billion, including $4 billion in cash. <b>The bank raised its cash offer</b> to about $7 billion and its total proposal to roughly $14 billion, but the Justice Department has balked at the offer. If a deal is not reached in the coming days, the <b>Justice Department might announce a lawsuit against the bank</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Also on Wednesday, Judge Jed S. Rakoff of the Federal District Court in Manhattan <b>ordered Bank of America to pay a penalty of nearly $1.3 billion</b>, nine months after federal prosecutors persuaded a jury to find Bank of America liable for selling questionable loans to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the government-controlled mortgage finance giants, before the financial crisis. The case exposed <b>fraudulent practices in one of Countrywideâs lending programs</b> nicknamed the hustle, which linked bonuses to how fast bankers could originate loans.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> ARGENTINAâS RELENTLESS FOE <span class="divider"> | </span></span> âThe hedge fund firm of billionaire Paul E. Singer has about 300 employees, yet it has managed to force Argentina, a nation of 41 million people, into a position where it now has to contemplate a humbling surrender,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/30/in-hedge-fund-argentina-finds-relentless-foe">Peter Eavis and Alexandra Stevenson write in DealBook</a></b>. Argentina on Wednesday failed to make scheduled payments on its government bonds. The country has the money to pay the bonds, but a federal court in Manhattan has ruled that unless Argentina settles its debt dispute with Mr. Singerâs firm, Elliott Management, it is barred from paying its main bondholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After more than five hours of meetings on Wednesday, <b>the sides failed to reach an agreement</b> and the court-appointed mediator said that Argentina would âimminently be in default.â Because a $539 million interest payment was not made, the ratings agency Standard &amp; Poorâs said that Argentina was in default on those bonds. The government of Argentina can now try to restart negotiations with investors it has repeatedly called âvultures,â who have for years refused to accept anything other than full repayment. Or it can remain ensnared in a default that could weigh on the countryâs fragile economy and unsettle global markets, Mr. Eavis and Ms. Stevenson write.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe campaign against Argentina shows how driven and deep-pocketed hedge funds can sometimes <b>wield influence outside of the markets they bet in</b>,â they write. As a hedge fund, Elliottâs pursuit of Argentina is motivated by a desire to make money. But, Mr. Eavis and Ms. Stevenson add, there is also something of a crusade about the battle that reveals the worldview of Mr. Singer, a Republican donor with libertarian leanings, who has spoken out when he thinks that governments and companies have damaged the rights of creditors. It is not clear whether Elliott expected Argentina to meet its demands by now. But the big question is <b>whether Argentina will ever pay Elliott what it wants</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For more on the battle over Argentinaâs debt, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/30/q-a-whats-behind-the-battle-over-argentinas-debt">check out DealBookâs Q. and A</a></b>.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">SYNCHRONY FINANCIAL TO BEGIN TRADING <span class="divider"> | </span></span> General Electricâs retail lending arm, now known as Synchrony Financial, raised about $2.9 billion in its initial public offering on Wednesday, as G.E. moved to shrink its finance division, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/30/g-e-s-retail-finance-arm-raises-2-9-billion-in-i-p-o">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced writes</a></b>. The business, which is expected to begin trading on the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday, priced its shares at $23 each, <b>at the low end of its expected price range</b>, valuing the newly independent company at $19.1 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSynchronyâs I.P.O., the largest in the United States so far this year, constitutes one of the biggest steps yet by G.E. to <b>reduce its dependence on GE Capital</b>,â Mr. de la Merced writes. The division was once the biggest driver of G.E.âS earnings, but ultimately hurt the company during the financial crisis. <b>G.E. has since moved to shed assets</b> outside its core industrial and health care businesses. Synchrony is the biggest provider of store-branded credit cards in the country, having financed $93.9 billion in sales last year. The business earned nearly $2 billion in profit, atop $11.3 billion in revenue.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Challenger job cut report</b> is out at 7:30 a.m. Gallupâs <b>job creation index</b> is released at 8:30 a.m. Weekly <b>jobless claims</b> are out at 8:30 a.m. The <b>employment cost index</b> is released at 8:30 a.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The <b>Senate Banking Committee</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. to examine financial products for students. The Senate Banking Committeeâs <b>Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Protections</b> holds a hearing at 2 p.m. to examine the Government Accountability Office report on expectations of government support for bank holding companies.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BNP PARIBAS POSTS RECORD LOSS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The French banking giant BNP Paribas reported a record quarterly loss on Thursday after it recently agreed to plead guilty to criminal charges and pay an $8.9 billion penalty for violating United States sanctions, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/31/bnp-paribas-posts-loss-on-huge-u-s-settlement">Mark Scott writes in DealBook</a></b>. As part of the deal, BNP Paribas said it had set aside 5.75 billion euros, or $7.70 billion, to cover the financial penalties doled out by the American authorities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The provisions pushed the bank <b>into a second-quarter net loss of â¬4.3 billion</b>. The bank reported a net profit of â¬1.8 billion in the period a year earlier. The bank said that it had set aside a further â¬200 million to meet future compliance needs related to the settlement.</p>
